---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="How This Works" active="how">
  <h1>How this works</h1>

  <h2 style="margin-top:0;">What it looks at overnight</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    Every night and morning, this system checks about 90 stocks for two things: is the price
    moving a lot more than usual before the market opens, and is there real trading volume
    behind that move (not just a couple of stray trades). It also reads the news, checks
    what Bitcoin and the futures markets did overnight, and looks at each stock's own
    history — a 3% move is a big deal for a slow-moving name and nothing at all for one that
    swings 8% most days.
  </p>

  <h2>What it can tell you</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    Which six names on the watchlist deserve to be on your screen at 9:29, and why — in plain
    language, with the actual pre-market high, low, and yesterday's close, and every warning
    sign (thin trading, a wide spread, a history of getting halted, a stock that barely has any
    trading history yet) called out clearly rather than buried in a number.
  </p>

  <h2>Can I trust these numbers?</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    A quote is two live offers, side by side: the highest price anyone is willing to pay right
    now (the <strong>bid</strong>), and the lowest price anyone is willing to sell for (the
    <strong>ask</strong>). When those two numbers sit close together, that's a healthy, real
    market — people are actively trading the stock and roughly agree on what it's worth this
    second.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    When the market's closed, or a stock just isn't trading much, the last bid and ask freeze in
    place — and because they froze at different moments, they can drift apart into something
    that doesn't make sense anymore. You might see a stock's last bid sitting at $195 next to an
    ask up at $230. That's not a typo and it's not a glitch worth panicking over — it's just what
    a sleeping market looks like once nobody's actually making one.
  </p>

  <div class="card-grid" style="margin:18px 0 24px;">
    <div class="card" style="border-color: var(--status-critical);">
      <h3 style="color: var(--status-critical); margin-bottom:10px;">Sleeping — not a real quote</h3>
      <p style="font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, monospace; font-size:1.1rem; margin:0 0 8px;">
        bid $195.00 &nbsp;/&nbsp; ask $230.00
      </p>
      <p style="margin:0; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size:0.88rem;">
        A 17.9% gap between two frozen leftovers. Nobody would actually trade at either price
        right now — this name gets dropped, automatically, not ranked on this number.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="border-color: var(--status-good);">
      <h3 style="color: var(--status-good); margin-bottom:10px;">Live — a real market</h3>
      <p style="font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, monospace; font-size:1.1rem; margin:0 0 8px;">
        bid $195.55 &nbsp;/&nbsp; ask $195.57
      </p>
      <p style="margin:0; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size:0.88rem;">
        Two cents apart, seconds old. This is what a name actually trading pre-market looks like
        — this is the kind of quote a pick is built on.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="lede">
    Premonition picks at 9:15 — by then, pre-market's been trading for hours, and the names
    actually worth watching are printing fresh, tight quotes like the second example. The
    overnight junk is gone by the time it matters.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    The reassurance underneath all of this: the dashboard only ever uses quotes that are both
    live and sane at the moment it picks — checked for freshness (is this actually recent, or a
    stale leftover?) and for a plausible spread (is this gap even realistic for this stock?). A
    name still showing a frozen or absurd quote at 9:15 gets dropped automatically, the same way
    the first example above would be. That's not a separate safety feature bolted on top — it's
    the same check doing two jobs at once: it protects you from ever seeing a fabricated number,
    and it tells the system which names are actually asleep and don't belong in the running. A
    stock that can't produce a real quote can't produce a real, tradable move.
  </p>

  <h2>What it can't tell you</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    When to press the button. Nothing can. At a two-minute hold, the tape in front of you at
    9:30 matters more than anything this system read overnight — that's not a limitation we're
    working to fix, it's just true, and pretending otherwise would make this more dangerous, not
    more useful. This system describes what's likely to move and why. It never tells you to
    enter, exit, size, or time a trade.
  </p>

  <h2>Six names, not one idea wearing six hats</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    If Bitcoin has a bad night, five different crypto-adjacent stocks can all look like
    independent opportunities when they're really the same bet five times. So at most two of
    the six picks ever come from the same underlying story — the six names always represent at
    least three genuinely different ideas.
  </p>

  <h2>How the scoreboard works</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    Every morning's picks get graded against what the market actually did in the first five
    minutes after the open. That gets compared to two strategies anyone could run without any of
    this: picking the six stocks that moved the most overnight, and picking the six with the
    most overnight trading. Those are the bar. If this system can't beat both of them, the
    scoreboard says so, in plain language, on the home page — that comparison is never hidden,
    softened, or left off a bad week.
  </p>

  <h2>The promise</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    Right now, every pick on this dashboard is <strong>shadow mode</strong> — tracked and
    graded, but explicitly not a recommendation, and labeled that way everywhere it appears.
    That doesn't change until the scoreboard shows this system actually beating both dumb
    strategies over a real stretch of mornings. If it never does, this dashboard says exactly
    that, and the picks stay off, permanently. A system that can't prove it's better than
    guessing has no business pretending otherwise.
  </p>
</Base>
